# Terraform state — contains the generated database password and admin API key in
# PLAINTEXT. random_password writes its result to state; that is unavoidable. Committing
# this would publish the credentials that Secret Manager exists to protect.
*.tfstate
*.tfstate.*
*.tfstate.backup

# Saved plans. A plan file embeds the values of every variable, including sensitive ones.
*.tfplan

# Provider binaries — hundreds of MB, re-downloaded by init.
.terraform/
.terraform.tfstate.lock.info

# Local overrides
*.auto.tfvars
override.tf
override.tf.json
*_override.tf

# NOT ignored, on purpose:
#   terraform.*.tfvars    — environment config is code and belongs in review
#   .terraform.lock.hcl   — pins provider versions; committing it is the point
#   bootstrap/terraform.tfstate is still ignored above. It holds no secrets (a bucket and
#   a list of enabled APIs), but it does record real resource IDs, and the bucket it
#   creates is trivially recreated by re-running bootstrap.
